       <!-- Article Title Goes Here -->
       <tr><td colspan="3" style="padding: 10px;">
           <!-- Article Title Goes Here -->
 
 
  
  
    <div style="margin-bottom:10px;"><a href="http://go.techtarget.com/r/19880843/6483512"><font face="arial, trebuchet, verdana" size="3"><b>Why should you store a VM on an SMB file share?</b></font></a><br></div>
    <div style="margin-bottom:10px;"><font face="arial, trebuchet, verdana" color="#666666" size="2">Brien Posey, Contributor</font><br></div>
    
   
    <table width="300" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="right">
    <tr><td valign="top" style="margin:5px;"> 
   
  </td></tr>
   </table>
   <span style="font-family : arial, trebuchet, verdana; color: #000000; font-size: x-small;">
  Before the release of Windows Server 2012 and Hyper-V 3.0, data centers had multiple options for storing VMs, but an SMB file share was not one of them. Should you take advantage of this new storage support? </span><br>
  <font face="verdana" size="-2"><a href="http://go.techtarget.com/r/19880844/6483512">READ THIS ANSWER</a></font>
  <br><br><br>
 
  
  
    <a href="http://go.techtarget.com/r/19880845/6483512"><font face="arial, trebuchet, verdana" size="2"><b>Cheaper fault tolerance with Hyper-V Replica</b></font></a><br>
    <span style="font-family : arial, trebuchet, verdana; color: #000000; font-size: x-small;">
  Failover clusters are an excellent way to handle fault tolerance, but they don't come cheap. Hyper-V Replica can create fault tolerance without the added cluster expense. </span><br>
  <font face="verdana" size="-2"><a href="http://go.techtarget.com/r/19880846/6483512">READ THIS TIP</a></font>
  <br><br><br>
 
  
  
    <a href="http://go.techtarget.com/r/19880847/6483512"><font face="arial, trebuchet, verdana" size="2"><b>Scalable storage by way of a VSA deployment</b></font></a><br>
    <span style="font-family : arial, trebuchet, verdana; color: #000000; font-size: x-small;">
  Using virtual storage appliances to build scalable storage for virtual infrastructure is cheap, flexible and convenient. Here are some tips to get started. </span><br>
  <font face="verdana" size="-2"><a href="http://go.techtarget.com/r/19880848/6483512">READ THIS TIP</a></font>
  <br><br><br>
 
  
  
    <a href="http://go.techtarget.com/r/19880849/6483512"><font face="arial, trebuchet, verdana" size="2"><b>Using hypervisor tiering for cheaper, easier management</b></font></a><br>
    <span style="font-family : arial, trebuchet, verdana; color: #000000; font-size: x-small;">
  Tiered storage has made significant improvements to storage performance. Hypervisor tiering can bring similar benefits to multiple hypervisor management. </span><br>
  <font face="verdana" size="-2"><a href="http://go.techtarget.com/r/19880850/6483512">READ THIS TIP</a></font>
  <br><br><br>
  </td>
